PART 4: T_3 lex T_3 — CYCLIC LEX CYCLIC
  T_3 lex T_3 gives n=9, H=3159
  The internal blocks are 3-cycles, not transitive
======================================================================
  Scores: [np.int64(4), np.int64(4), np.int64(4), np.int64(4), np.int64(4), np.int64(4), np.int64(4), np.int64(4), np.int64(4)]
  All scores = 4? True (REGULAR)
  H(T_3 lex T_3) = 3159
  max_H(9) = 3357
  Ratio: 0.9410
  T_3 lex T_3 achieves 94.1% of maximum!

  NOTE: T_3 lex T_3 is REGULAR (all scores 4).
  The Paley tournament at p=7 has n=7 vertices (wrong size).
  At n=9, the maximizer likely has a different structure.

======================================================================
PART 5: WHEN DOES LEX PRODUCT ACHIEVE max_H?
======================================================================
    n         Construction    H_lex    max_H   Achieves max?
    3      T_3 (trivially)        3        3             YES
    4       no lex product      N/A        5              NO
    6          T_3 lex T_2       45       45             YES
    9          T_3 lex T_3     3159     3357              NO

  CONCLUSION: Lex products give maximizers at n=3,6 (=3*1, 3*2)
  but NOT at n=4,9. The pattern is NOT simply 'blow up T_3'.
  At odd prime n=7,11: Paley tournaments achieve max, not lex products.
  At even n: lex products of T_3 with smaller tournaments can help.

